sentences: Olu Dara Jones (born Charles Jones III, January 12, 1941) is an American cornetist, guitarist, and singer.
Olu Dara was born Charles Jones III January 12, 1941, in Natchez, Mississippi.
His mother, Ella Mae, was born in 1911 in Canton, Mississippi.
From 1959 to 1964 he was a musician in the Navy, which he described as a priceless educational experience.
In 1964, he moved to New York City and changed his name to Olu Dara, which means "God is good" in the Yoruba language.

His first album, In the World: From Natchez to New York (1998), revealed another aspect of his musical personality: the leader and singer of a band immersed in African-American tradition, playing an eclectic mix of blues, jazz, and storytelling, with tinges of funk, African popular music, and reggae.
Dara played on the album Illmatic (1994) by his son, rapper Nas, and on the song "Dance" (2002), also by Nas, and he sang on Nas's song "Bridging the Gap" (2004).
